00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:16.660
this content, design, delivery.

00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:19.150
I know we have a whole
entire range of people--

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:21.740
from designers,
to app designers,

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:24.180
to even some business
development people in here--

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:26.550
so we're going to talk about
a lot of different ways.

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:28.660
From the basics--
how can everyone

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:31.070
walk away here and create
an amazing presentation--

00:06:31.070 --> 00:06:34.740
but even more, how do you find
a way to become the best version

00:06:34.740 --> 00:06:36.650
of yourself as a presenter?

00:06:36.650 --> 00:06:38.710
And the first thing
that we're going to do

00:06:38.710 --> 00:06:39.910
is actually content.

00:06:39.910 --> 00:06:43.400
And so our content-- part of
the design delivery process

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:45.870
is that engaging
content always wins.

00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:48.300
But what does engaging
content really mean?

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:51.450
So with content, there's
four different things

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:53.470
that I always
recommend when it comes

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:55.190
to making a great presentation.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:57.670
And this goes from whether
it's a deck that you're

00:06:57.670 --> 00:06:59.780
going to send out,
to a pitch deck,

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:01.800
to even if you're
pitching an idea.

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:05.555
And the first is that
every single presentation

00:07:05.555 --> 00:07:10.040
that you have should have
this thing called a big idea.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:13.340
And a big idea is an
idea that formulates

00:07:13.340 --> 00:07:15.140
around the whole
entire presentation,

00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:16.730
it's your central argument.

00:07:16.730 --> 00:07:18.480
And by the way, in the
middle of this talk

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:21.621
we're actually going to create
a presentation from scratch.

00:07:21.621 --> 00:07:23.120
So we're going to
have a lot of fun.

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:25.360
So the big idea is the
main central argument

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:26.410
of your presentation.

00:07:26.410 --> 00:07:29.300
It's what people are
compelled to believe in.

00:07:29.300 --> 00:07:31.850
And furthermore with that is
that every good presentation

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:32.940
should have a structure.

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:35.240
So when I say structure--
how many people

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:38.630
here know about the rule
of three in presentations?

00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:41.589
So the rule of three in
communication and presentations

00:07:41.589 --> 00:07:43.880
is that if I tell you there
are six things to remember,

00:07:43.880 --> 00:07:45.150
there are five
things to remember,

00:07:45.150 --> 00:07:46.524
it's a little bit
more difficult.

00:07:46.524 --> 00:07:48.940
But if you're able to condense
your presentation down

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:52.840
into three easy
points-- they're, I say,

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:55.780
Twitter handles-- you're more
likely to walk away and have

00:07:55.780 --> 00:07:57.830
someone to be able to
retain the information.

00:07:57.830 --> 00:08:00.460
The next is a call to action.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.490
Every presentation--
I tell you this.

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:04.130
When I think of the
word presentation,

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:05.830
I don't think of just
the formal presentation

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:07.000
we're doing here on stage.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.445
I think of going home,
talking to my fiancee,

00:08:09.445 --> 00:08:11.070
and saying what do
you want for dinner?

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:13.820
Then I present my ideas,
she presents her ideas,

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:15.100
and we go back and forth.

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:17.030
It can even be a
conversation, or if you're

00:08:17.030 --> 00:08:20.200
pitching an idea such
as a design concept.

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:21.670
Presentations can be anything.

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:24.260
But here's the thing-- any
time when you go and present

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:27.100
an idea or just
an argument, it's

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:28.790
important to have
a call to action.

00:08:28.790 --> 00:08:31.870
And when I say call to action,
there are three different ones.

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:35.490
One is an offer, such as
if you buy this, you'll

00:08:35.490 --> 00:08:39.809
get X. Next is demand, do this.

00:08:39.809 --> 00:08:42.789
And the next and final one is
actually more of a question,

00:08:42.789 --> 00:08:47.150
such as what if you went
home and ate a donut

00:08:47.150 --> 00:08:48.325
and became happy?

00:08:48.325 --> 00:08:49.700
And the reason
why I say donut is

00:08:49.700 --> 00:08:50.830
that that's actually
the presentation

00:08:50.830 --> 00:08:51.870
we're going to create.

00:08:51.870 --> 00:08:54.440
We're going to create a
live and full argument

00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:57.190
on why everyone in
this room who might not

00:08:57.190 --> 00:08:59.530
think donuts are healthy,
would now believe

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:00.610
that donuts are healthy.

00:09:00.610 --> 00:09:03.600
And so we're going to do it
with the same exact process.

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:06.820
So from going around this
room, how many people

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:10.334
here actually love donuts?

00:09:10.334 --> 00:09:11.500
Good, there's not that many.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:12.250
I love this.

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:13.900
All right, challenge accepted.

00:09:13.900 --> 00:09:16.600
So how many people here don't
think that donuts are actually

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:17.500
healthy for you?

00:09:20.210 --> 00:09:21.700
Kind of wrong,
but it's all good.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.590
Donuts are delicious, though,
they're great for your mind.

00:09:23.590 --> 00:09:24.423
They make you happy.

00:09:24.423 --> 00:09:26.570
And so with that
being said, that

00:09:26.570 --> 00:09:28.270
will be the central argument.

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:31.830
The big idea is that for all
the donut lovers in here that

00:09:31.830 --> 00:09:34.900
now have my back, we're going
to create and work on a reason

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:37.660
why everyone else in the
room should love a donut.

00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:40.260
So just going around, why
should people in this room

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:41.230
love donuts?

00:09:41.230 --> 00:09:42.210
And this is where
I'm going to ask you

00:09:42.210 --> 00:09:44.710
questions, because we're going
to come up with our own pitch

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:45.311
together.

