And the thing is, we actually
thought to ourselves,

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:46.530
what if the judges all
had perfect 20/20 vision?

00:20:46.530 --> 00:20:50.422
How can they understand what
does it feel like to be blind?

00:20:50.422 --> 00:20:52.255
And so we created this
slide right here when

00:20:52.255 --> 00:20:55.190
we pitched to the company
was imagine if you were

00:20:55.190 --> 00:20:58.630
a child growing up in Guatemala
and you couldn't see anything,

00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:01.000
but you wanted to learn,
you wanted to lead,

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.460
and you wanted to
do great things.

00:21:02.460 --> 00:21:05.990
But your sight isn't there.

00:21:05.990 --> 00:21:07.950
And if you want
to be better, you

00:21:07.950 --> 00:21:10.426
need to see the people
that believe in you.

00:21:10.426 --> 00:21:12.050
And this is actually
what they pitched.

00:21:12.050 --> 00:21:15.470
They said, for those here,
who here has 20/20 vision?

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:18.000
And the judges raised their
hands, and we were right.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:20.020
And they never-- and
they asked, so you all

00:21:20.020 --> 00:21:22.370
might not know what it's
be like to be blind.

00:21:22.370 --> 00:21:23.630
However, though, if
you're looking right here,

00:21:23.630 --> 00:21:24.620
this is what it's like.

00:21:24.620 --> 00:21:28.000
But for $5, if you invest in
us today, you can do this,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:32.930
and a child can see and
make a huge difference.

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:33.830
And they loved it.

00:21:33.830 --> 00:21:35.670
And that was one of
most memorable moments

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:37.369
in that whole
entire presentation.

00:21:37.369 --> 00:21:39.410
And it was one of those
feelings where I thought,

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:41.440
that's how design
can be memorable.

00:21:41.440 --> 00:21:43.450
So for anyone here
today can take away

00:21:43.450 --> 00:21:45.980
something when it comes to
presentations, whether it's

00:21:45.980 --> 00:21:48.320
with content but for
design, is that simplicity

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:51.830
wins because they need
you, as the presenter.

00:21:51.830 --> 00:21:53.680
They need to be understand
but, most of all,

00:21:53.680 --> 00:21:54.880
it needs to be memorable.

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:56.830
There's no reason why
slides can't be fun.

00:21:56.830 --> 00:21:58.067
PowerPoint is fun.

00:21:58.067 --> 00:21:59.900
I know everyone, when
they come to our firm,

00:21:59.900 --> 00:22:02.140
they think, what can we
do besides PowerPoint?

00:22:02.140 --> 00:22:04.650
We have all these cool
tips and tricks in our bag,

00:22:04.650 --> 00:22:07.030
but I always say, what's
wrong with PowerPoint?

00:22:07.030 --> 00:22:08.780
You can do amazing
things with PowerPoint.

00:22:08.780 --> 00:22:10.404
This right here was
done in PowerPoint,

00:22:10.404 --> 00:22:13.620
but it delivered a
very effective message.

00:22:13.620 --> 00:22:17.430
So with content design comes
one the most important things,

00:22:17.430 --> 00:22:20.340
and that's actually
rules of thirds

00:22:20.340 --> 00:22:22.770
is that, with every
grid slide here--

00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:25.950
how many people here are
photographers on their off time

00:22:25.950 --> 00:22:26.550
here?

00:22:26.550 --> 00:22:30.130
So what do you-- when you
think of the rule of thirds,

00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:31.956
you always think of
your central figure

00:22:31.956 --> 00:22:34.330
should not be in the center
when you're creating a slide.

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:36.790
It's actually you want to be
able to position your figure,

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:38.550
wherever your main
point of focus

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:40.420
is, to the left or
the right so you have

00:22:40.420 --> 00:22:43.360
a little bit of slide-- or
little bit of room to the left

00:22:43.360 --> 00:22:46.047
or right to actually
put in there some words.

00:22:46.047 --> 00:22:48.630
That's what we recommend for a
lot of our presentation slides.

00:22:48.630 --> 00:22:50.470
For anyone going home
today and creating

00:22:50.470 --> 00:22:52.960
their own presentation, think
about the rule of thirds.

00:22:52.960 --> 00:22:54.670
If you put it in the middle,
you're forcing something.

00:22:54.670 --> 00:22:56.520
But you're putting
to the left or right,

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:57.969
you're actually coexisting.

00:22:57.969 --> 00:22:59.510
And that's what you
want with slides,

00:22:59.510 --> 00:23:02.380
is that you want to coexist
when it comes to photography.

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:04.024
You never want to impose on top.

00:23:04.024 --> 00:23:05.440
And here's some
of our other sides

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:07.460
that we created,
is that, for this,

00:23:07.460 --> 00:23:10.820
when it comes to slides like
this, you think of photography.

00:23:10.820 --> 00:23:14.389
This is very, very, very
boring energy usage.

00:23:14.389 --> 00:23:15.680
How can you make this more fun?

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:17.846
And we see this in a lot
of corporate presentations,

00:23:17.846 --> 00:23:21.110
is that you actually think,
OK, this gets the point across,

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:22.750
but how do you
make it memorable?

00:23:22.750 --> 00:23:24.210
And this is what
I recommend doing.

00:23:24.210 --> 00:23:26.210
Let's bold the important
points, and let's throw

00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:27.450
an image at the end.

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:28.980
Next, what do you
think about when

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:30.470
you share a graph like this?

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:32.610
We all seen graphs
like this where

00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:35.140
it's a chart or some kind
of information presented

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:37.270
and you think to
yourself, wow, what can we

00:23:37.270 --> 00:23:38.750
do here to make it more fun?

00:23:38.750 --> 00:23:39.480
Very simple.

00:23:39.480 --> 00:23:42.420
Why don't we turn
it into a graphic?

00:23:42.420 --> 00:23:45.000
And it's simple tools like
this where you can do it

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.540
and where you can turn very
minute and boring information

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:50.520
into something fun
and more lively.

00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:51.772
Design should be fun.

00:23:51.772 --> 00:23:53.730
And the thing is, like,
how many people in here

00:23:53.730 --> 00:23:54.688
are actually designers?

00:23:56.900 --> 00:23:59.300
I'm not a designer, and
I'm proud not to be is

00:23:59.300 --> 00:24:02.880
because if you learn these
simple design principles,

00:24:02.880 --> 00:24:05.400
anyone can become a great
presentation designer.

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:07.660
And I say that is that there
are many tools out there.

00:24:07.660 --> 00:24:09.701
So this tool right here,
you can create something

00:24:09.701 --> 00:24:12.430
using Canva, for
example, a very popular--

00:24:12.430 --> 00:24:15.290
Canva or Piktochart
is another one.

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:17.920
And those tools can create
amazing infographics for you

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:19.040
very quickly.

00:24:19.040 --> 00:24:21.297
If you're ever in a rush
for presentations and you

00:24:21.297 --> 00:24:23.755
can't hire an agency or you
don't-- you can't just spawn it

00:24:23.755 --> 00:24:26.171
off to another designer, I
recommend there's a tool called

00:24:26.171 --> 00:24:29.220
Haiku Deck, and it actually puts
in your presentation content

00:24:29.220 --> 00:24:32.470
for you and actually allocates
it into a way where it does not

00:24:32.470 --> 00:24:35.900
feel like there's too much slide
or too much text per slide.

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:38.060
But there are many
good tools out there

00:24:38.060 --> 00:24:40.059
to make you an effective
presentation designer.

00:24:40.059 --> 00:24:42.600
It's just very important to look
for them and to keep in mind

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:45.140
that being simple,
memorable, and understandable

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:49.620
for any type of designer is
the most important thing.

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:53.370
Now this is the fun
part is the delivery.

00:24:53.370 --> 00:24:58.110
So when it comes to delivering
slides, presentations,

00:24:58.110 --> 00:25:00.840
or even arguments or
even conversations,

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:04.110
it's very important to have
powerful body language.

00:25:04.110 --> 00:25:05.350
May I have a volunteer?

00:25:05.350 --> 00:25:08.054
Preferably a donut lover?

00:25:08.054 --> 00:25:10.220
May have a volunteer in
here to actually demonstrate

00:25:10.220 --> 00:25:13.350
some good body language?

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:15.570
I'm going to choose you,
Gus, to come up here.

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:18.170
This is my co-founder,
Gus, over here.

00:25:18.170 --> 00:25:21.160
And so-- whatever
I say, you do, OK?

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:21.880
Just trust me.

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:22.280
GUS MURILLO: OK.

00:25:22.280 --> 00:25:22.680
KENNY NGUYEN: OK.

00:25:22.680 --> 00:25:24.050
That's the way I sold it to him.

00:25:24.050 --> 00:25:25.400
That's my presentation to him.

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:27.830
So, ways to have
better body language.

00:25:27.830 --> 00:25:30.100
The first thing is
to always remember,

00:25:30.100 --> 00:25:31.990
when you give a
presentation, no one

00:25:31.990 --> 00:25:33.740
wants to have a grumpy
person in the room.

00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:35.670
It's very important to smile.

00:25:35.670 --> 00:25:37.279
So smile.

00:25:37.279 --> 00:25:38.070
Let's smile at him.

00:25:38.070 --> 00:25:39.400
Let's wake him up a little bit.

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:40.550
Just smile at him.

00:25:40.550 --> 00:25:42.300
So it's very important to smile.

00:25:42.300 --> 00:25:44.786
Smiling actually alerts the
other human in front of you

00:25:44.786 --> 00:25:46.660
that you're ready and
you're ready to engage.

00:25:46.660 --> 00:25:49.370
If you're grumpy and you're
walking up and you're sad,

00:25:49.370 --> 00:25:52.100
it pulls off a very
different opinion of you.

00:25:52.100 --> 00:25:55.950
Second is that you always
want an open posture.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:58.544
Imagine if you're like this
talking in a presentation.

00:25:58.544 --> 00:25:59.960
And it's one of
those things where

00:25:59.960 --> 00:26:02.906
it's very hard to do
because, when you're nervous,

00:26:02.906 --> 00:26:04.280
you're going up,
you're like, OK,

00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:05.620
let me think about something.

00:26:05.620 --> 00:26:06.870
It looks like you're not sure.

00:26:06.870 --> 00:26:09.990
But you're open, it shows a
much more positive and more

00:26:09.990 --> 00:26:11.870
engaging type of body language.

00:26:11.870 --> 00:26:14.210
The third is to
use hand gestures.

00:26:14.210 --> 00:26:16.750
So you can do this.

00:26:16.750 --> 00:26:18.160
It's hand gestures.

00:26:18.160 --> 00:26:21.055
And I say it in a controlled
way is that imagine I present it

00:26:21.055 --> 00:26:22.790
like this.

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.400
You don't know if I'm excited.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:26.700
And just by using
one hand, it shows

00:26:26.700 --> 00:26:28.200
a completely different
way of saying

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:29.890
you don't know if I'm excited.

00:26:29.890 --> 00:26:31.254
It seems very, very different.

00:26:31.254 --> 00:26:32.670
That's the power
of hand gestures.

00:26:32.670 --> 00:26:34.045
It can actually
show your emotion

00:26:34.045 --> 00:26:35.790
and it shows your point.

00:26:35.790 --> 00:26:39.250
The fourth is to actually
have eye contact.

00:26:39.250 --> 00:26:40.619
So let's stare him down.

00:26:40.619 --> 00:26:41.410
GUS MURILLO: Again?

00:26:41.410 --> 00:26:42.890
KENNY NGUYEN: Yeah, again.

00:26:42.890 --> 00:26:45.100
Sorry, man, you're in
my direct line of sight.

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:46.840
So is eye contact.

00:26:46.840 --> 00:26:49.750
So I'll tell you all a secret
trick that one of my friends

00:26:49.750 --> 00:26:51.970
taught me, is that
for those people here

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:53.690
that are very afraid
of eye contact,

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:55.970
there's a trick called
looking in the forehead.

00:26:55.970 --> 00:26:57.410
I'm looking at your
forehead right now, man,

00:26:57.410 --> 00:26:58.760
but it looks like I'm
staring directly at you.

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:00.100
It's very creepy, I know.

00:27:00.100 --> 00:27:01.040
Just bear with me.

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:03.380
But the thing is, though,
that's a very effective way

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:05.220
is that, when you're able
to look someone in the eye

00:27:05.220 --> 00:27:07.511
and tell them a message that
they might not believe in,

00:27:07.511 --> 00:27:09.574
or an argument, a call
to action, a big idea,

00:27:09.574 --> 00:27:11.240
but you're able to
look them in the eyes

00:27:11.240 --> 00:27:13.970
and show that
genuine authenticity,

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:16.122
it's much more compelling
for you as a presenter.

00:27:16.122 --> 00:27:18.730
But if I look away I'm
telling you something,

00:27:18.730 --> 00:27:20.740
you want that attention on you.

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:22.680
And so that's why eye
contact is so important.

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:26.345
And the fifth and most important
point is do it naturally.

00:27:26.345 --> 00:27:27.720
You should not
look like a creep.

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:28.290
Sorry, man.

00:27:28.290 --> 00:27:30.650
We just totally just bombarded
you with some of that.

00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:34.820
But if I'm just doing this
and talking, pull me out.

00:27:34.820 --> 00:27:35.970
NYPD, come get me.

00:27:35.970 --> 00:27:37.310
And you don't want that.

00:27:37.310 --> 00:27:39.106
You want something that
looks very natural.

00:27:39.106 --> 00:27:40.980
And that's why it's so
important to rehearse.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:41.835
Gus, thank you, man.

00:27:41.835 --> 00:27:42.140
GUS MURILLO: All right.

00:27:42.140 --> 00:27:44.440
KENNY NGUYEN: So let's give
him a round of applause.

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:46.500
He had no clue, and that's
how I sold it to him.

00:27:46.500 --> 00:27:48.652
But next thing is,
how do you rehearse?

00:27:48.652 --> 00:27:50.110
Because when you
think to yourself,

00:27:50.110 --> 00:27:51.620
body language,
oh, I can do this.

00:27:51.620 --> 00:27:53.680
I know-- I remember
how to do this.

00:27:53.680 --> 00:27:57.530
It's very important to
rehearse and create habits.

00:27:57.530 --> 00:28:01.450
Presentations,
public speaking, they

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:03.570
become great through habits.

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:05.350
Sure, you can present
once or twice.

00:28:05.350 --> 00:28:07.860
But if you don't-- aren't
able to critique yourself,

00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:10.540
there's a very different
way for you to learn.

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:13.410
And I recommend three different
ways to actually rehearse.

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:15.270
One-- does anyone
ever record themselves

00:28:15.270 --> 00:28:17.536
before a presentation?

00:28:17.536 --> 00:28:18.910
It's really hard
to watch, right,

00:28:18.910 --> 00:28:21.493
sometimes in the first-- yeah,
it's actually really miserable.

00:28:21.493 --> 00:28:24.790
For my first-- for my TEDxTalk,
and actually the same talk

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:28.260
I did at HubSpot recently,
I actually gave a talk

00:28:28.260 --> 00:28:31.370
and I watched it and I thought,
man, I don't like this.

00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:33.950
And I watched it about nine
times, and I just said,

00:28:33.950 --> 00:28:35.349
I'm gonna scrap it.

00:28:35.349 --> 00:28:37.140
And that's really
flustering to understand,

00:28:37.140 --> 00:28:39.348
but here's the thing, is
that if I'm able to do that,

00:28:39.348 --> 00:28:41.270
I'm able to watch it
and say, if I'm not

00:28:41.270 --> 00:28:43.110
able to sit through
my own presentation,

00:28:43.110 --> 00:28:46.920
why would someone else want
to sit through it, as well.

00:28:46.920 --> 00:28:49.070
And sure enough,
we redid it, and I

00:28:49.070 --> 00:28:52.890
think the video now has
almost 40,000 views on YouTube

00:28:52.890 --> 00:28:55.180
and 10,000 on SlideShare.

00:28:55.180 --> 00:28:57.630
And it was actually telling
the story about "Shark Tank."

00:28:57.630 --> 00:29:02.610
How did we make-- we
turned down "Shark Tank"

00:29:02.610 --> 00:29:04.544
and in my TED Talk, we
explained how we turned

00:29:04.544 --> 00:29:05.710
the process of "Shark Tank."

00:29:05.710 --> 00:29:07.580
And the challenge is how
do you make that sound fun.

00:29:07.580 --> 00:29:10.081
And so watching it over and
over and over again to the point

00:29:10.081 --> 00:29:11.496
where we knew where
it sounded fun

00:29:11.496 --> 00:29:14.040
and I would enjoy hearing the
story was that breaking point.

00:29:14.040 --> 00:29:17.509
And so finding a way to rehearse
and watch yourself-- pull out

00:29:17.509 --> 00:29:19.550
that webcam, pull out that
iPhone, watch yourself

00:29:19.550 --> 00:29:21.387
rehearse and critique yourself.

00:29:21.387 --> 00:29:23.095
Did you say something
that sounded weird?

00:29:23.095 --> 00:29:25.390
Do you say a lot of
and's, um's, or ah's?

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:26.900
Or did you have
body language that

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:30.010
just made you look
boring, creepy,

00:29:30.010 --> 00:29:33.310
or did you not enunciate
your words correctly?

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:34.990
It's very important
to record yourself

00:29:34.990 --> 00:29:37.660
because then you'll find
your biggest critic.

00:29:37.660 --> 00:29:41.370
Next is always find
your own unique ritual.

00:29:41.370 --> 00:29:43.730
So my ritual before
I go and present

00:29:43.730 --> 00:29:46.350
is I love listening
to stand-up comedy.

00:29:46.350 --> 00:29:48.617
And it just makes me happy.

00:29:48.617 --> 00:29:50.700
And the thing is, before
I go into a presentation,

00:29:50.700 --> 00:29:51.880
I should be happy.

00:29:51.880 --> 00:29:53.920
So there are different
ways for you to actually

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:55.320
prepare yourself mentally.

00:29:55.320 --> 00:29:56.940
So does anyone
here want to share

00:29:56.940 --> 00:29:59.273
some of things they do before
they go on a presentation?

00:30:02.522 --> 00:30:03.980
AUDIENCE: I wasn't
at the TED Talk,

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:07.370
but there was a woman that
did a Superwoman pose, so I--

00:30:07.370 --> 00:30:08.331
KENNY NGUYEN: Oh yeah.

00:30:08.331 --> 00:30:08.830
Yeah.

00:30:08.830 --> 00:30:10.830
That's actually one of the
most common ones I actually

00:30:10.830 --> 00:30:12.780
hear is, like, the
Superwoman pose actually

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:14.165
just gets you really revved up.

00:30:14.165 --> 00:30:14.870
I think that's great.

00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:16.620
I think I would love
to try it for myself.

00:30:16.620 --> 00:30:17.890
I should do that.

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:19.292
Any other ones?

00:30:19.292 --> 00:30:21.916
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I like to listen
to Rocky's "Eye of the Tiger."

00:30:21.916 --> 00:30:22.747
It gets me--

00:30:22.747 --> 00:30:24.080
KENNY NGUYEN: Yeah, that's good.

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:24.690
That's good.

00:30:24.690 --> 00:30:26.390
Music is actually
another big one.

00:30:26.390 --> 00:30:27.640
Yoga I've heard.

00:30:27.640 --> 00:30:29.616
Tony Robbins actually
jumps on a trampoline.

00:30:29.616 --> 00:30:31.741
I've read that, like, before
he went on Dreamforce,

00:30:31.741 --> 00:30:34.140
he just jumps on a trampoline
to get that adrenaline up,

00:30:34.140 --> 00:30:36.635
those endorphins, and he gets
them really amped for, like,

00:30:36.635 --> 00:30:37.990
his six-hour workshop.

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:38.920
It's incredible.

00:30:38.920 --> 00:30:41.530
And so it's good, though, is
that you have these rituals.

00:30:41.530 --> 00:30:45.320
And to prepare yourself is one
of the most overlooked things

00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:47.331
is that, sure, I'm just
giving a presentation.

00:30:47.331 --> 00:30:49.080
But you always want
to be in your element.

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:50.871
If you're able to find
what makes you happy

00:30:50.871 --> 00:30:54.790
beforehand, that makes you
really energetic, use that.

00:30:54.790 --> 00:30:55.890
Keep that in mind.

00:30:55.890 --> 00:30:58.120
And the third is
to actually find

00:30:58.120 --> 00:31:00.117
friends that can critique you.

00:31:00.117 --> 00:31:02.450
And that's one of the most
overlooked thing, because you

00:31:02.450 --> 00:31:05.190
always think, oh, you
know, I'm in this alone.

00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:08.074
If you have people in
the room-- and I'm not--

00:31:08.074 --> 00:31:09.490
I usually ask this
question, who--

00:31:09.490 --> 00:31:11.170
how many people here in
the room have actually

00:31:11.170 --> 00:31:13.220
wanted to fall asleep when
they've seen someone else here

00:31:13.220 --> 00:31:13.950
present.

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:16.040
And usually it's a really
uncomfortable question.

00:31:16.040 --> 00:31:17.990
I always tell them, those are
the people that you should

00:31:17.990 --> 00:31:20.031
go to, because those are
the people that tell you

00:31:20.031 --> 00:31:21.710
straight up that
will tell you you

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:23.169
can do better on
your presentation.

00:31:23.169 --> 00:31:24.709
And that's very
important, is to find

00:31:24.709 --> 00:31:26.850
those friends or those
colleagues, those coworkers,

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:28.730
those siblings that will
tell you straight up,

00:31:28.730 --> 00:31:30.400
I didn't understand
what you had to say.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:32.720
So to close, for
this formal part,

00:31:32.720 --> 00:31:34.587
is that there are three
things that everyone

00:31:34.587 --> 00:31:36.920
should remember when it comes
to an amazing presentation

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:37.670
experience.

00:31:37.670 --> 00:31:41.480
One is that content
should always be engaging

00:31:41.480 --> 00:31:43.230
and should always
have a structure

00:31:43.230 --> 00:31:46.720
and should always, always,
always have a call to action.

00:31:46.720 --> 00:31:51.080
Next is that design should
be simple, memorable,

00:31:51.080 --> 00:31:53.970
and most importantly,
memorable and understandable.

00:31:53.970 --> 00:31:56.010
Now finally, delivery.

00:31:56.010 --> 00:31:58.990
Delivery, always
find your element.

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:00.330
Have that great body language.

00:32:00.330 --> 00:32:03.150
But it's most importantly find
what makes you comfortable.

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:05.205
Because at the end of
the day, if I'm up here

00:32:05.205 --> 00:32:07.080
and I'm teaching
you and telling you,

00:32:07.080 --> 00:32:09.770
why don't you become like
Steve Jobs when you go present?

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:11.840
You're gonna think,
I'm not Steve Jobs.

00:32:11.840 --> 00:32:13.410
You want to find
your own element.

00:32:13.410 --> 00:32:15.090
And that's why we
have this process.

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:17.590
The process here isn't to teach
you to be like someone else.

00:32:17.590 --> 00:32:19.300
This process here is
to teach you to be

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:20.760
the best version of yourselves.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:24.250
And for people here that
know the poet Maya Angelo,

00:32:24.250 --> 00:32:27.880
people always remember
what you say, what you do,

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:30.840
but people will never forget
how you made them feel.

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:34.490
That is the true essence
of an amazing presenter.

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:37.195
And if you remember that
quote in any presentation

00:32:37.195 --> 00:32:40.530
that you give, it's how
you make others feel,

00:32:40.530 --> 00:32:45.240
I promise you you'll be the most
amazing presenter in the room.

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:46.206
Thank you.

00:32:46.206 --> 00:32:49.574
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:49.574 --> 00:32:51.490
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you
for that presentation.

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:53.281
You guys definitely
know what you're doing.

00:32:53.281 --> 00:32:56.030
So I have a handful
of questions about how

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:58.760
you can take all the
experience that you guys have

00:32:58.760 --> 00:33:01.770
and how we can apply it to
our day-to-day work here.

00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:05.940
So one of the first questions
I have is all this information

00:33:05.940 --> 00:33:07.710
is pretty fantastic
if you have a week

00:33:07.710 --> 00:33:10.920
to prepare for a presentation,
but the reality is

00:33:10.920 --> 00:33:12.420
there's going to
be situations where

00:33:12.420 --> 00:33:13.878
I get an email in
the morning and I

00:33:13.878 --> 00:33:16.530
have to give a presentation
in three hours.

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:18.610
Do you have any tips
or tricks or advice

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:21.820
on how to prepare presentations
under a time crunch?

00:33:21.820 --> 00:33:22.820
KENNY NGUYEN: Yes, I do.

00:33:22.820 --> 00:33:24.490
And, like, feel
free to chime in.

00:33:24.490 --> 00:33:28.250
For our stuff is that I actually
get pretty frequent requests

00:33:28.250 --> 00:33:30.570
to do presentations if, let's
say, a speaker drops out.

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:33.040
I'll go and give a
presentation the day of.

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:35.240
And the best thing I've
always learned to do

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:37.980
is, like, I talked it a
little bit about earlier,

00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:40.965
creating that type of
structure in your presentation.

00:33:40.965 --> 00:33:44.720
The intro, three main points,
and then a call to action.

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:48.246
I make sure, before I go on
anything else-- design, or even

00:33:48.246 --> 00:33:50.370
delivery-- I have that kind
of content right there.

00:33:50.370 --> 00:33:53.070
Because at the end of the
day, that's your message.

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:55.052
And so before I even
open up PowerPoint

00:33:55.052 --> 00:33:56.510
and you're in a
time crunch, if you

00:33:56.510 --> 00:33:58.600
have less than six hours
or even less than two hours

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:00.850
to put together a deck,
that's what I recommend doing,

00:34:00.850 --> 00:34:03.431
is, like, come up with your
structure and your message

00:34:03.431 --> 00:34:04.805
before you take
on anything else.

00:34:04.805 --> 00:34:06.721
I don't know, do you
want to chime in on that?

00:34:06.721 --> 00:34:08.500
GUS MURILLO: And keep
in mind that content

00:34:08.500 --> 00:34:09.699
is the most important thing.

00:34:09.699 --> 00:34:12.210
You shouldn't be spending too
much-- if you have six hours,

00:34:12.210 --> 00:34:14.293
you shouldn't be spending
five hours on your deck.

00:34:14.293 --> 00:34:15.770
Focus on what
you're going to say.

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:18.830
Spend your last bit of
time putting-- making sure

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:21.605
that your slides look good,
but honestly just the biggest

00:34:21.605 --> 00:34:22.730
tip is just keep it simple.

00:34:22.730 --> 00:34:24.590
There's tools out
there like Haiku Deck.

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:26.877
Or if you just honestly want
to make something really

00:34:26.877 --> 00:34:28.460
quick and simple in
PowerPoint, that's

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:31.013
good because, if you try to
spend too much time making

00:34:31.013 --> 00:34:32.429
the most detailed
slides, it's not

00:34:32.429 --> 00:34:34.370
going to matter if you're
not prepared for what you're

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:36.703
going to say and if you don't
have a clear and memorable

00:34:36.703 --> 00:34:38.320
structure.

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:40.500
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:42.489
A lot of these rules
sound really excellent

00:34:42.489 --> 00:34:43.980
when you're giving
a presentation

00:34:43.980 --> 00:34:45.710
to a large audience.

00:34:45.710 --> 00:34:47.440
Do you think it
changes at all when

00:34:47.440 --> 00:34:49.409
you go from a stage
and a platform

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:51.505
to a small room or
a conference table

00:34:51.505 --> 00:34:54.510
and you're presenting to
a small set of coworkers?

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:57.210
KENNY NGUYEN: I actually learned
that by doing some workshops--

00:34:57.210 --> 00:34:59.990
we do a lot of workshops--
I actually change a lot more

00:34:59.990 --> 00:35:01.380
based on the audience size.

00:35:01.380 --> 00:35:04.990
For example, if we had,
like, a stadium crowd here,

00:35:04.990 --> 00:35:07.910
or, like, a crowd like 1,000,
for example, I normally

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:11.190
wouldn't do and engage with
them that much compared

00:35:11.190 --> 00:35:13.350
to if it's a smaller room.

00:35:13.350 --> 00:35:15.040
And so like, let's
say, like five

00:35:15.040 --> 00:35:17.130
to, like, 50 people,
that's when activities

00:35:17.130 --> 00:35:19.590
would be more-- I would be
more open to activities.

00:35:19.590 --> 00:35:21.670
It matters because
the reason is is,

00:35:21.670 --> 00:35:23.880
like, you can only engage
so much people in the room

00:35:23.880 --> 00:35:24.710
at a time.

00:35:24.710 --> 00:35:26.490
But the smaller it is,
let's make it more intimate.

00:35:26.490 --> 00:35:27.706
Let's make it a conversation.

00:35:27.706 --> 00:35:29.470
And so I'll tell
anyone that, like, when

00:35:29.470 --> 00:35:32.282
they give a presentation, if
you have, like, a small room,

00:35:32.282 --> 00:35:33.240
make it a conversation.

00:35:33.240 --> 00:35:34.920
But if it's a
bigger room, that's

00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:37.672
where a more formal
presentation would be OK.

00:35:37.672 --> 00:35:39.657
I don't know, what do you think?

00:35:39.657 --> 00:35:40.490
GUS MURILLO: Agreed.

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:42.823
Just make sure your activities
are tailored specifically

00:35:42.823 --> 00:35:43.420
to your group.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:47.250
Like, for groups of five to 10,
which a lot of small meetings

00:35:47.250 --> 00:35:49.420
are, you can actually
get every one of them

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:51.480
to answer your question
and to chime in,

00:35:51.480 --> 00:35:54.330
rather than here you have
to get a crowd to come up

00:35:54.330 --> 00:35:55.800
with a few suggestions.

00:35:55.800 --> 00:35:58.810
For a group to five to 10, you
can really get some-- a lot

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:01.690
of back and forth, and actually
turn it into a conversation.

00:36:01.690 --> 00:36:03.290
Because groups that
small don't want

00:36:03.290 --> 00:36:06.004
to sit for 45 minutes,
or even 30 minutes

00:36:06.004 --> 00:36:07.920
and just be talked to
for that period of time,

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:09.020
they want to talk.

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:10.360
KENNY NGUYEN: Yeah,
everyone has a voice.

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:12.401
And that's why I wanted
to do the donut activity.

00:36:12.401 --> 00:36:14.280
It's always fascinating,
because usually it's

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:15.350
like-- it's usually
a hit or miss

00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:17.560
when it comes to people,
like, actually engaging back.

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:19.268
Because a small room,
everyone would just

00:36:19.268 --> 00:36:21.090
start-- just bombard
me with, like, this

00:36:21.090 --> 00:36:22.560
is why I love a donut,
this is why I love a donut.

00:36:22.560 --> 00:36:23.249
And it's cool.

00:36:23.249 --> 00:36:25.290
But, like, when it comes
to, like, larger crowds,

00:36:25.290 --> 00:36:27.706
you know, you have the feeling
of, should I say something.

00:36:27.706 --> 00:36:29.410
But once a person say
something, then we

00:36:29.410 --> 00:36:31.140
have one person
that just chimes in,

00:36:31.140 --> 00:36:32.390
then the others will chime in.

00:36:32.390 --> 00:36:33.473
It usually takes that one.

00:36:33.473 --> 00:36:36.160
But with a smaller room and
you have like 5 to 10 people,

00:36:36.160 --> 00:36:39.070
usually you're getting
it left and right.

00:36:39.070 --> 00:36:42.110
MALE SPEAKER: So Google
has the unique problem

00:36:42.110 --> 00:36:44.255
where we might have a
meeting in the morning

00:36:44.255 --> 00:36:47.360
where we're talking with our
coworkers on the same floor,

00:36:47.360 --> 00:36:49.610
an hour later we may have a
meeting with our coworkers

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:53.280
in India or
California or Brazil.

00:36:53.280 --> 00:36:55.900
Do you have any advice
on how to communicate

00:36:55.900 --> 00:36:58.440
when you're doing it
digitally across [INAUDIBLE],

00:36:58.440 --> 00:36:59.570
or something like that?

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:00.361
KENNY NGUYEN: Yeah.

00:37:00.361 --> 00:37:02.610
So whenever I think of
presentations-- or webinars

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:05.980
or just doing something
remotely with colleagues,

00:37:05.980 --> 00:37:07.670
like complete--
like this even comes

00:37:07.670 --> 00:37:10.180
in when we do client
pitches is that we've

00:37:10.180 --> 00:37:13.430
had to learn the hard way
on how to engage them.

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:15.040
When you do something
on the computer,

00:37:15.040 --> 00:37:18.160
you're fighting with what's
available on the other person's

00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:18.820
computer.

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:21.025
It's like internet, it's
YouTube, it's cat videos.

00:37:21.025 --> 00:37:22.109
It's-- it can be anything.

00:37:22.109 --> 00:37:24.274
And the way that we always
thought about it is this,

00:37:24.274 --> 00:37:26.140
is like how do we
get it to be direct.

00:37:26.140 --> 00:37:27.730
So I'll answer in two parts.

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:29.310
One is, if you
have a small group

00:37:29.310 --> 00:37:31.080
for five 10 people,
that's when I

00:37:31.080 --> 00:37:34.020
say I would engage with people,
is I would ask them questions.

00:37:34.020 --> 00:37:35.686
I wouldn't just go
sit down and present.

00:37:35.686 --> 00:37:37.930
And if I do, I keep that
at a minimum, where there's

00:37:37.930 --> 00:37:40.235
a break in between where I
can ask them questions, what

00:37:40.235 --> 00:37:42.710
do they think, and give a
time where they can actually

00:37:42.710 --> 00:37:44.630
submit in questions in the box.

00:37:44.630 --> 00:37:48.430
However, though, if it's
from, like, 25 to 50 people,

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:49.930
that's a little bit
different, where

00:37:49.930 --> 00:37:51.990
it's a little bit harder because
you have a whole entire team

00:37:51.990 --> 00:37:54.700
call and you don't know who's
really paying attention.

00:37:54.700 --> 00:37:55.754
I mean, quite frankly.

00:37:55.754 --> 00:37:57.170
So what I recommend,
in that case,

00:37:57.170 --> 00:38:00.210
is that, if you use a slide
deck, keep it very simple.

00:38:00.210 --> 00:38:04.045
If it's-- it's even harder
to present off a webinar,

00:38:04.045 --> 00:38:06.420
because you're not there having
that personal connection.

00:38:06.420 --> 00:38:08.420
So that simple, memorable,
understandable design

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:09.430
applies to that.

00:38:09.430 --> 00:38:11.919
If there's no slide
deck, though, I

00:38:11.919 --> 00:38:14.210
would recommend actually
asking questions and engaging.

00:38:14.210 --> 00:38:17.060
But at the same time,
have an agenda call.

00:38:17.060 --> 00:38:20.100
And clearly make sure who's
involved on that call.

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:21.920
I mean, you want
piggyback on this?

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:22.670
GUS MURILLO: Yeah.

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:26.260
Especially for smaller meetings
between-- and you're pitching

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:28.700
ideas, make sure
that you go into it

00:38:28.700 --> 00:38:32.066
and they go into it knowing,
like, I guess an agenda,

00:38:32.066 --> 00:38:33.440
but it's mainly
just a structure.

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:35.148
So they know that
they're gonna come away

00:38:35.148 --> 00:38:36.220
with these few things.

00:38:36.220 --> 00:38:37.786
And that might not be a deck.

00:38:37.786 --> 00:38:39.160
Just make sure
that you have that

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:41.130
written down and sent to them.

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:42.030
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:38:42.030 --> 00:38:43.080
So in the next
few minutes, we're

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:45.240
gonna open this up to the
audience for questions.

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:47.210
So if you have something
you want to ask,

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:51.800
please stand by one of
the two microphones.

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:57.990
So in your opinion, you know
how to give good presentations,

00:38:57.990 --> 00:39:01.350
and so you probably have a sense
of what a bad presentation is.

00:39:01.350 --> 00:39:04.614
What is the absolute worst
thing a person can do?

00:39:04.614 --> 00:39:06.030
KENNY NGUYEN: Read
off 200 slides.

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:06.560
MALE SPEAKER: 200 slides.

00:39:06.560 --> 00:39:07.810
KENNY NGUYEN: No, I'm kidding.

00:39:07.810 --> 00:39:10.512
Well, like, no, the
worst thing I've seen--

00:39:10.512 --> 00:39:12.380
and I hope everyone
takes this to heart--

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:14.860
is when the presenter
is everywhere,

00:39:14.860 --> 00:39:16.800
there's no structure
in the presentation.

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:19.277
I kid you not, when you
have a structure, a roadmap,

00:39:19.277 --> 00:39:21.610
you know where you're going--
and it can be suspenseful.

00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:23.818
You don't have to reveal
everything in the beginning.

00:39:23.818 --> 00:39:26.050
But if you have a
roadmap that can tell,

00:39:26.050 --> 00:39:26.855
like, there are
three things we're

00:39:26.855 --> 00:39:28.470
gonna learn today-- content,
design, and delivery,

00:39:28.470 --> 00:39:29.841
you know where I'm taking you.

00:39:29.841 --> 00:39:30.340
That's fine.

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:32.350
But if I'm telling you all
these different stories

00:39:32.350 --> 00:39:34.610
and you don't know where we're
going, that's a big problem.

00:39:34.610 --> 00:39:36.880
It's always to say, like, I
like to have presentations

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:37.840
that have a structure.

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:40.080
Still surprise me,
but at least, like,

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:42.370
let me know where we're
going, where we're at.

00:39:42.370 --> 00:39:44.120
GUS MURILLO: And the
biggest thing for me,

00:39:44.120 --> 00:39:47.500
since I-- I guess-- I mainly
contributed to the design

00:39:47.500 --> 00:39:49.960
portion of the book,
was just everyone

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:51.409
putting too much on the slide.

00:39:51.409 --> 00:39:52.950
And that just happened
so frequently.

00:39:52.950 --> 00:39:57.186
It just-- keep in mind that what
you're gonna send to the people

00:39:57.186 --> 00:39:59.560
later is not what you should
be showing to them right now

00:39:59.560 --> 00:40:00.750
on stage.

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:02.200
And that's the
worst thing for me.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:05.122
That guy with the 200 slides,
having 60 bullet points a slide

00:40:05.122 --> 00:40:06.330
where you can't even read it.

